<h1 align="center" style="margin-left: 40; margin-right: 40"><!--mstheme--><font face="Book Antiqua, Times New Roman, Times" color="#660000">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<!--mstheme--></font></h1>
<!--mstheme--><font face="Times New Roman, Times"><!--mstheme--></font>
<h1 align="center" style="margin-left: 40; margin-right: 40"><!--mstheme--><font face="Book Antiqua, Times New Roman, Times" color="#660000">Alexander
Lernet-Holenia<!--mstheme--></font></h1>
<!--mstheme--><font face="Times New Roman, Times">
<p align="center" style="margin-left: 40; margin-right: 40">Austrian novelist,
poet, dramatist and translator</p>
<!--msthemeseparator--><p align="center"><img src="romhorsa.gif"></p>
<p align="left" style="margin-left: 40; margin-right: 40">Lernet-Holenia was
born in Vienna in 1897, participated in both World Wars as an officer, traveled
widely, especially in South America. He received many awards for his literary
work as a dramatist, novelist and poet. President of the Austrian P.E.N. Club
from 1968 to 1972. He died in St. Wolfgang, Austria, in 1976.</p>
<!--msthemeseparator--><p align="center"><img src="romhorsa.gif"></p>
<p align="left" style="margin-left: 40; margin-right: 40">Lernet-Holenia's
plays, for which he was awarded the Kleist Prize in 1926, brought him early
fame. He was one of the last literary representatives of the old Austria with a
sharp eye for the present. Similar to Graham Greene's, his work can be divided
into entertainment, primarily written to earn money, and more serious literary
work. Lernet-Holenia himself considered his poetry his greatest achievement.
This should not detract from the greatness of his best novels – <i>Die
Standarte</i>, <i>Mars im Widder</i>, <i>Beide Sizilien</i>, <i>Der Gaf von
Saint-Germain</i> and <i>Der Graf Luna</i> – and his masterful stories, such
as <i>Der Baron Bagge</i> and <i>Der blinde Gott</i>, collected in <i>Mayerling</i>.
And there can be no doubt that some of the lighter work, like <i>Der Mann im Hut</i>,
<i>Die Auferstehung des Maltravers</i> or <i>Ich war Jack Mortimer</i>  – written in Lernet-Holenia's unmistakable
prose style reminiscent of Heinrich von Kleist – to this
day makes for suspenseful entertainment.</p>
<!--msthemeseparator--><p align="center"><img src="romhorsa.gif"></p>
<p align="left" style="margin-left: 40; margin-right: 40">&nbsp;</p>
<!--mstheme--></font>
